<h3>cHAPTER 4 iNITIALIZATION bLOCKS</h3>
<p>You have already seen two ways to initialize a data field :</p> 

<ol> 

<li>By setting a value in constructor </li> 

 

<li>By assigning a value in constructor</li> 

</ol> 

 

<p>There is a third mechanism in java to initialize variable that is initialization block</p> 

 

<p>Class declaration can contain arbitrary block of code. These block are executed whenever an object of that class is constructed.</p> 

 

<pre> 

   private static int nextID; 

   private int id; 

    

   { 

       id = nextID; 

       nextID++; 

   } 

  </pre>  

 

<p>In this example, the id field is initialized in the object initialization block, no matter which constructor is used to construct the object.</p> 

 

<p>The initialization block runs first, and then the body of the constructor is executed. </p> 

 

<p>We should try to initialize the code in constructor only .</p> 

 

<p>It is legal to set fields in initialization blocks even if they are only defined later in the class. However, to avoid circular definitions, it is not legal to read from fields that are only initialized later.</p> 

 

<p>With so many ways of initializing the data fields . So we will summarize the process of what happens when a constructor is called </p> 

<ol> 

<li>If the first line calls of the constructor calls a second constructor then the second constructor runs before the calling constructor</li> 

 

<li>All data field are initialized to the default value (0, false or null)</li> 

 

<li>All field initializers and initialization block are executed in the order in which they occur in the class</li> 

 

<li>The body of the constructor is executed</li> 

</ol> 

 

 

<p>It is good practice to initialize the field variable in constructor as it would be easy for everyone as it is not good to be  dependent on how they occur in the class .</p> 

 

<p>To initialize a static field, either supply an initial value or use a static initialization block. You have already seen the first mechanism:</p> 

 

<pre> 

private static int nextId = 1; 

 

static 
{ 
    Random generator = new Random(); 
    nextId = generator.nextInt(10000); 
} 

</pre> 

<p>Static initialization occurs when the class is first loaded. Like instance fields, static fields are 0, false, or null unless you explicitly set them to another value. All static field initializers and static initialization blocks are executed in the order in which they occur in the class declaration.</p> 

 
